n: habitational name from any of numerous places so named throughout Germany (three of which are now in Poland)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Johan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Older Scottish spelling of <b>Joan</b> , which was traditionally pronounced as two syllables."],"variants":[{"name":"Jens","meanings":["Mainly Danish: variant of   Johan ."]},{"name":"Jöns","meanings":["Mainly Danish: variant of   Johan ."]},{"name":"Jan","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]},{"name":"Jon","meanings":["Simplified spelling of   John   or a short form of   Jonathan .  The name is borne by the Canadian singer  Jon Vickers  (  b. 1926 ) and the American actor  Jon Voight  (  b. 1938 )."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Claesson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Hild.","Swedish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Clas</i>, a shortened form of <i>Niklas</i> (see   Nicholas  ). In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the variant <b>Klasson</b>. Compare   Clason   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]},{"name":"Clason","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto.","Americanized form (and a less common Swedish variant) of Swedish   Classon   or <b>Klasson</b>.","Americanized form of German, Danish, Norwegian, and Dutch   Clasen   or   Classen  , or of any other patronymic from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Nik(o)laus</i> or <i>Nikla(a)s</i> (see   Nicholas  )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702079,"age":5,"year":"1520","julianDay":2276228,"title":"The Stockholm Bloodbath","description":"A mass execution of Swedish nobles by Danish king Christian II is known as the Stockholm Bloodbath. Christian II invaded Sweden in 1519 and took hold of Stockholm in September 1520. Over 80 nobles were executed for heresy on November 8 and 9. The outrage from the executions led to the Swedish removal of support of the Kalmar Union.","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Stockholm-Bloodbath","urlTitle":"Britannica - Stockholm Bloodbath","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702080,"age":8,"year":"1523","julianDay":2277324,"title":"Swedish War of Liberation","description":"The Swedish War of Liberation was a civil war led by nobleman Gustav Vasa. As Christian II heard of the rebellion, he confronted Vasa's men, who won the battle at Brunbacks Ferry. Christian II was defeated by the Swedes in Stockholm and a truce was agreed upon. Vasa was given as a hostage as a show of good faith until the treaty was signed. The Danish King did not keep his word and Vasa was held as a prisoner for two years until his escape. A bounty was placed on Vasa's head. Vasa worked to inspire many to join his cause and lived under disguise until the Danes surrendered in 1525.","url":"https://www.sweden.org.za/swedish-monarchy-gustav-vasa.html","urlTitle":"Sweden.org - Swedish Monarchy Gustav Vasa","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702084,"age":12,"year":"1527","julianDay":2278785,"title":"The Protestant Reformation","description":"The Protestant Reformation in Sweden occurred as King Gustav Vasa of Sweden, aided by his chancellor Laurentius Andreae, a Swedish Lutheran clergyman, broke ties with Rome and the Roman Catholic church in 1527.","url":"https://www.britannica.com/topic/Church-of-Sweden","urlTitle":"Britannica - Church of Sweden","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702085,"age":25,"year":"1540","julianDay":2283533,"title":"First Full Swedish Translation of the Bible","description":"The first full Swedish translation of the Bible, known as the Gustav Bible, was completed by Olaus Petri and Laurentius Andreae and published in 1540.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702086,"age":29,"year":"1544","julianDay":2284994,"title":"Sweden Becomes Lutheran Nation","description":"Sweden officially declared itself a Lutheran nation in 1544.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1357053,"age":36,"year":"1551","julianDay":2287551,"description":"Sweden seized territory of Estonia.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Johan Claesson Von Zijlen Neuendorff was born in 1515, in Rostock, Rostock, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Germany, his father, Wedig von Zule  zu Tuschow zu Tessin, was 25 and his mother, Beate von Ritzerow, was 23. He married Adeleid Wackerbarth in 1557, in Skälboö, Östergötland, Sweden. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1558, in Berga, Kronoberg, Sweden, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1515–1558":"1515–1558","1537–Male":"1537–Surnud","1515–1610":"1515–1610","1561–1586":"1561–1586","1490–1516":"1490–1516","1492–1535":"1492–1535","1561":"1561","4 Apr. 1535":"4. aprill 1535","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1558":"1558","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","1523":"1523","1544":"1544","1610":"1610","1520":"1520","1586":"1586","1